[{"sha":"f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e","author":{"name":"Abin Shahab","email":"aa5e48ffaae751ccd8830df151a27b555951f193@linkedin.com"},"message":"Resolves coredump caused by `tf.data.experimental.save` with prefetch

Repeat and prefetch in combination cause the snapshot reader Initialize function to be invoked multiple times.
However, there is nothing to prefetch on the very last iteration. This results in Prefetch issuing a CancelThreads call while the snapshot thread is trying to initialize. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/6446dda92eaadf11d22377e2354307642d739d73/tensorflow/core/kernels/data/prefetch_dataset_op.cc#L151

Currently the dataset reference counting is done asymmetrically. The reference increment happens at the end of initialization, where as the reference decrement
happens in a destructor. When prefetch cancels the snapshot thread, it errors out of the initialization function. And stops calling the reference increment. However, the reference decrement happens regardless, as it is in the destructor which always is invoked during cleanup. This results in an attempt to decrement the null dataset pointer, and therefore a segmentation fault.
This is different from all other dataset ops, where the dataset reference increment happens in the constructor and the decrement happens in the destructor, which are symmetric.

The solution to this is to ensure that the dataset reference is always initialized to nullptr, and to check for null when decrementing the dataset reference.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e"},{"sha":"4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984","author":{"name":"Koan-Sin Tan","email":"0f50d6f3c0f5df9b282683ddabaf63e2d4d09d2c@gmail.com"},"message":"[nnapi delegate] fix a trivial redundant comment and a typo","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984"},{"sha":"78ea1f17049f4b933294985a77bd9d8cc1aeb54f","author":{"name":"Renjie Liu","email":"a3cbff63481c3dc2f9e28ce2b84d61daae727f6d@google.com"},"message":"Fold pad/padv2 when the input shape == output shape.

This implementation is based on the example in tf.slim. It exhibits a run time and space complexity of O(T + N), where T is the number of thresholds and N is the size of predictions. Metrics that rely on standard implementation instead exhibit a complexity of O(T * N). It could save a lot of memory when N is large.

Added a unit test to verify the memory consumption. Under eager context, the ratio of memory between old and new approach is between 80 and 500. Set the limit to 50 to avoid the flakiness.

Change-Id: If2e8136b961d7e054a0ba3a2f323e7ebc51f0da3","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cache-Cloud/tensorflow/commits/6dfadbcd5fbec0198c4a4ebe3174dd15716ff681"},{"sha":"41cc9e51b82b2655d75beaf619af6798e6a63be3","author":{"name":"Scott Zhu","email":"65d81eb4203ec9a5a8b298abc5184127125bc9fe@google.com"},"message":"Update keras metrics to use memory efficient alternative when collect values for evenly distributed thresholds.

This implementation is based on the example in tf.slim. It exhibits a run time and space complexity of O(T + N), where T is the number of thresholds and N is the size of predictions. Metrics that rely on standard implementation instead exhibit a complexity of O(T * N). It could save a lot of memory when N is large.

Added a unit test to verify the memory consumption. Under eager context, the ratio of memory between old and new approach is between 80 and 500. Set the limit to 50 to avoid the flakiness.

[{"sha":"f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e","author":{"name":"Abin Shahab","email":"aa5e48ffaae751ccd8830df151a27b555951f193@linkedin.com"},"message":"Resolves coredump caused by `tf.data.experimental.save` with prefetch

Repeat and prefetch in combination cause the snapshot reader Initialize function to be invoked multiple times.
However, there is nothing to prefetch on the very last iteration. This results in Prefetch issuing a CancelThreads call while the snapshot thread is trying to initialize. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/6446dda92eaadf11d22377e2354307642d739d73/tensorflow/core/kernels/data/prefetch_dataset_op.cc#L151

Currently the dataset reference counting is done asymmetrically. The reference increment happens at the end of initialization, where as the reference decrement
happens in a destructor. When prefetch cancels the snapshot thread, it errors out of the initialization function. And stops calling the reference increment. However, the reference decrement happens regardless, as it is in the destructor which always is invoked during cleanup. This results in an attempt to decrement the null dataset pointer, and therefore a segmentation fault.
This is different from all other dataset ops, where the dataset reference increment happens in the constructor and the decrement happens in the destructor, which are symmetric.

The solution to this is to ensure that the dataset reference is always initialized to nullptr, and to check for null when decrementing the dataset reference.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e"},{"sha":"4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984","author":{"name":"Koan-Sin Tan","email":"0f50d6f3c0f5df9b282683ddabaf63e2d4d09d2c@gmail.com"},"message":"[nnapi delegate] fix a trivial redundant comment and a typo","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984"},{"sha":"b2befac15624886810c2176fa88fb9a6790cc0ac","author":{"name":"Berkin Ilbeyi","email":"5f773b6479653d0f1ae8fe9abb2a70525c143dd2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Move constant earlier and assign alternate mem allocations for constants

Additionally, minor tweaks to LICM/while loop analysis passes:

    loops.

Change-Id: If2e8136b961d7e054a0ba3a2f323e7ebc51f0da3","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/6dfadbcd5fbec0198c4a4ebe3174dd15716ff681"},{"sha":"41cc9e51b82b2655d75beaf619af6798e6a63be3","author":{"name":"Scott Zhu","email":"65d81eb4203ec9a5a8b298abc5184127125bc9fe@google.com"},"message":"Update keras metrics to use memory efficient alternative when collect values for evenly distributed thresholds.

This implementation is based on the example in tf.slim. It exhibits a run time and space complexity of O(T + N), where T is the number of thresholds and N is the size of predictions. Metrics that rely on standard implementation instead exhibit a complexity of O(T * N). It could save a lot of memory when N is large.

Added a unit test to verify the memory consumption. Under eager context, the ratio of memory between old and new approach is between 80 and 500. Set the limit to 50 to avoid the flakiness.

[{"sha":"f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e","author":{"name":"Abin Shahab","email":"aa5e48ffaae751ccd8830df151a27b555951f193@linkedin.com"},"message":"Resolves coredump caused by `tf.data.experimental.save` with prefetch

Repeat and prefetch in combination cause the snapshot reader Initialize function to be invoked multiple times.
However, there is nothing to prefetch on the very last iteration. This results in Prefetch issuing a CancelThreads call while the snapshot thread is trying to initialize. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/6446dda92eaadf11d22377e2354307642d739d73/tensorflow/core/kernels/data/prefetch_dataset_op.cc#L151

Currently the dataset reference counting is done asymmetrically. The reference increment happens at the end of initialization, where as the reference decrement
happens in a destructor. When prefetch cancels the snapshot thread, it errors out of the initialization function. And stops calling the reference increment. However, the reference decrement happens regardless, as it is in the destructor which always is invoked during cleanup. This results in an attempt to decrement the null dataset pointer, and therefore a segmentation fault.
This is different from all other dataset ops, where the dataset reference increment happens in the constructor and the decrement happens in the destructor, which are symmetric.

The solution to this is to ensure that the dataset reference is always initialized to nullptr, and to check for null when decrementing the dataset reference.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MikeOwino/tensorflow/commits/f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e"},{"sha":"4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984","author":{"name":"Koan-Sin Tan","email":"0f50d6f3c0f5df9b282683ddabaf63e2d4d09d2c@gmail.com"},"message":"[nnapi delegate] fix a trivial redundant comment and a typo","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MikeOwino/tensorflow/commits/4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984"},{"sha":"b2befac15624886810c2176fa88fb9a6790cc0ac","author":{"name":"Berkin Ilbeyi","email":"5f773b6479653d0f1ae8fe9abb2a70525c143dd2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Move constant earlier and assign alternate mem allocations for constants

This implementation is based on the example in tf.slim. It exhibits a run time and space complexity of O(T + N), where T is the number of thresholds and N is the size of predictions. Metrics that rely on standard implementation instead exhibit a complexity of O(T * N). It could save a lot of memory when N is large.

Added a unit test to verify the memory consumption. Under eager context, the ratio of memory between old and new approach is between 80 and 500. Set the limit to 50 to avoid the flakiness.

[{"sha":"f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e","author":{"name":"Abin Shahab","email":"aa5e48ffaae751ccd8830df151a27b555951f193@linkedin.com"},"message":"Resolves coredump caused by `tf.data.experimental.save` with prefetch

Repeat and prefetch in combination cause the snapshot reader Initialize function to be invoked multiple times.
However, there is nothing to prefetch on the very last iteration. This results in Prefetch issuing a CancelThreads call while the snapshot thread is trying to initialize. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/6446dda92eaadf11d22377e2354307642d739d73/tensorflow/core/kernels/data/prefetch_dataset_op.cc#L151

Currently the dataset reference counting is done asymmetrically. The reference increment happens at the end of initialization, where as the reference decrement
happens in a destructor. When prefetch cancels the snapshot thread, it errors out of the initialization function. And stops calling the reference increment. However, the reference decrement happens regardless, as it is in the destructor which always is invoked during cleanup. This results in an attempt to decrement the null dataset pointer, and therefore a segmentation fault.
This is different from all other dataset ops, where the dataset reference increment happens in the constructor and the decrement happens in the destructor, which are symmetric.

The solution to this is to ensure that the dataset reference is always initialized to nullptr, and to check for null when decrementing the dataset reference.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e"},{"sha":"4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984","author":{"name":"Koan-Sin Tan","email":"0f50d6f3c0f5df9b282683ddabaf63e2d4d09d2c@gmail.com"},"message":"[nnapi delegate] fix a trivial redundant comment and a typo","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984"},{"sha":"3c80966daa507a263ef47943734b8f99a6d9d334","author":{"name":"HanBin Yoon","email":"024f177e31598ae518222a68ff45c86a00c86bd8@google.com"},"message":"Some fixes to using GpuOneShotAllocator in BefThunk.

This implementation is based on the example in tf.slim. It exhibits a run time and space complexity of O(T + N), where T is the number of thresholds and N is the size of predictions. Metrics that rely on standard implementation instead exhibit a complexity of O(T * N). It could save a lot of memory when N is large.

Added a unit test to verify the memory consumption. Under eager context, the ratio of memory between old and new approach is between 80 and 500. Set the limit to 50 to avoid the flakiness.

[{"sha":"f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e","author":{"name":"Abin Shahab","email":"aa5e48ffaae751ccd8830df151a27b555951f193@linkedin.com"},"message":"Resolves coredump caused by `tf.data.experimental.save` with prefetch

Repeat and prefetch in combination cause the snapshot reader Initialize function to be invoked multiple times.
However, there is nothing to prefetch on the very last iteration. This results in Prefetch issuing a CancelThreads call while the snapshot thread is trying to initialize. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/6446dda92eaadf11d22377e2354307642d739d73/tensorflow/core/kernels/data/prefetch_dataset_op.cc#L151

Currently the dataset reference counting is done asymmetrically. The reference increment happens at the end of initialization, where as the reference decrement
happens in a destructor. When prefetch cancels the snapshot thread, it errors out of the initialization function. And stops calling the reference increment. However, the reference decrement happens regardless, as it is in the destructor which always is invoked during cleanup. This results in an attempt to decrement the null dataset pointer, and therefore a segmentation fault.
This is different from all other dataset ops, where the dataset reference increment happens in the constructor and the decrement happens in the destructor, which are symmetric.

The solution to this is to ensure that the dataset reference is always initialized to nullptr, and to check for null when decrementing the dataset reference.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e"},{"sha":"4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984","author":{"name":"Koan-Sin Tan","email":"0f50d6f3c0f5df9b282683ddabaf63e2d4d09d2c@gmail.com"},"message":"[nnapi delegate] fix a trivial redundant comment and a typo","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984"},{"sha":"78ea1f17049f4b933294985a77bd9d8cc1aeb54f","author":{"name":"Renjie Liu","email":"a3cbff63481c3dc2f9e28ce2b84d61daae727f6d@google.com"},"message":"Fold pad/padv2 when the input shape == output shape.

This implementation is based on the example in tf.slim. It exhibits a run time and space complexity of O(T + N), where T is the number of thresholds and N is the size of predictions. Metrics that rely on standard implementation instead exhibit a complexity of O(T * N). It could save a lot of memory when N is large.

Added a unit test to verify the memory consumption. Under eager context, the ratio of memory between old and new approach is between 80 and 500. Set the limit to 50 to avoid the flakiness.

Repeat and prefetch in combination cause the snapshot reader Initialize function to be invoked multiple times.
However, there is nothing to prefetch on the very last iteration. This results in Prefetch issuing a CancelThreads call while the snapshot thread is trying to initialize. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/6446dda92eaadf11d22377e2354307642d739d73/tensorflow/core/kernels/data/prefetch_dataset_op.cc#L151

Currently the dataset reference counting is done asymmetrically. The reference increment happens at the end of initialization, where as the reference decrement
happens in a destructor. When prefetch cancels the snapshot thread, it errors out of the initialization function. And stops calling the reference increment. However, the reference decrement happens regardless, as it is in the destructor which always is invoked during cleanup. This results in an attempt to decrement the null dataset pointer, and therefore a segmentation fault.
This is different from all other dataset ops, where the dataset reference increment happens in the constructor and the decrement happens in the destructor, which are symmetric.

The solution to this is to ensure that the dataset reference is always initialized to nullptr, and to check for null when decrementing the dataset reference.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ashutosh1919/tensorflow/commits/f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e"},{"sha":"bdc55b1f6d05be3ca9f0b344da1c14943aaee988","author":{"name":"Ashutosh Hathidara","email":"8221b1507f31f1542863efde7afcbe0f973dd311@legatohealth.com"},"message":"Fixed Accuracy to be able to transform dynamically","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ashutosh1919/tensorflow/commits/bdc55b1f6d05be3ca9f0b344da1c14943aaee988"},{"sha":"4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984","author":{"name":"Koan-Sin Tan","email":"0f50d6f3c0f5df9b282683ddabaf63e2d4d09d2c@gmail.com"},"message":"[nnapi delegate] fix a trivial redundant comment and a typo","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ashutosh1919/tensorflow/commits/4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984"},{"sha":"935a632ba9c3618b4d1f127331b2d42c9687b67e","author":{"name":"A. Repeat and prefetch in combination cause the snapshot reader Initialize function to be invoked multiple times.
However, there is nothing to prefetch on the very last iteration. This results in Prefetch issuing a CancelThreads call while the snapshot thread is trying to initialize. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/6446dda92eaadf11d22377e2354307642d739d73/tensorflow/core/kernels/data/prefetch_dataset_op.cc#L151

Currently the dataset reference counting is done asymmetrically. The reference increment happens at the end of initialization, where as the reference decrement
happens in a destructor. When prefetch cancels the snapshot thread, it errors out of the initialization function. And stops calling the reference increment. However, the reference decrement happens regardless, as it is in the destructor which always is invoked during cleanup. This results in an attempt to decrement the null dataset pointer, and therefore a segmentation fault.
This is different from all other dataset ops, where the dataset reference increment happens in the constructor and the decrement happens in the destructor, which are symmetric.

The solution to this is to ensure that the dataset reference is always initialized to nullptr, and to check for null when decrementing the dataset reference.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e"},{"sha":"4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984","author":{"name":"Koan-Sin Tan","email":"0f50d6f3c0f5df9b282683ddabaf63e2d4d09d2c@gmail.com"},"message":"[nnapi delegate] fix a trivial redundant comment and a typo","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984"},{"sha":"6e43c06328a487b50b730388e9512248bb03a0ec","author":{"name":"A. This implementation is based on the example in tf.slim. It exhibits a run time and space complexity of O(T + N), where T is the number of thresholds and N is the size of predictions. Metrics that rely on standard implementation instead exhibit a complexity of O(T * N). It could save a lot of memory when N is large.

Added a unit test to verify the memory consumption. Under eager context, the ratio of memory between old and new approach is between 80 and 500. Set the limit to 50 to avoid the flakiness.

Repeat and prefetch in combination cause the snapshot reader Initialize function to be invoked multiple times.
However, there is nothing to prefetch on the very last iteration. This results in Prefetch issuing a CancelThreads call while the snapshot thread is trying to initialize. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/6446dda92eaadf11d22377e2354307642d739d73/tensorflow/core/kernels/data/prefetch_dataset_op.cc#L151

Currently the dataset reference counting is done asymmetrically. The reference increment happens at the end of initialization, where as the reference decrement
happens in a destructor. When prefetch cancels the snapshot thread, it errors out of the initialization function. And stops calling the reference increment. However, the reference decrement happens regardless, as it is in the destructor which always is invoked during cleanup. This results in an attempt to decrement the null dataset pointer, and therefore a segmentation fault.
This is different from all other dataset ops, where the dataset reference increment happens in the constructor and the decrement happens in the destructor, which are symmetric.

The solution to this is to ensure that the dataset reference is always initialized to nullptr, and to check for null when decrementing the dataset reference.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e"},{"sha":"4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984","author":{"name":"Koan-Sin Tan","email":"0f50d6f3c0f5df9b282683ddabaf63e2d4d09d2c@gmail.com"},"message":"[nnapi delegate] fix a trivial redundant comment and a typo","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984"},{"sha":"3b9c294fbcba17991005733eb189381db9ec4e58","author":{"name":"Anirudh Sriram","email":"d7d94d6565f008fd32dceffc8dd0b4f4fdfe5df4@google.com"},"message":"Update model links to TF Hub

Repeat and prefetch in combination cause the snapshot reader Initialize function to be invoked multiple times.
However, there is nothing to prefetch on the very last iteration. This results in Prefetch issuing a CancelThreads call while the snapshot thread is trying to initialize. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/6446dda92eaadf11d22377e2354307642d739d73/tensorflow/core/kernels/data/prefetch_dataset_op.cc#L151

Currently the dataset reference counting is done asymmetrically. The reference increment happens at the end of initialization, where as the reference decrement
happens in a destructor. When prefetch cancels the snapshot thread, it errors out of the initialization function. And stops calling the reference increment. However, the reference decrement happens regardless, as it is in the destructor which always is invoked during cleanup. This results in an attempt to decrement the null dataset pointer, and therefore a segmentation fault.
This is different from all other dataset ops, where the dataset reference increment happens in the constructor and the decrement happens in the destructor, which are symmetric.

The solution to this is to ensure that the dataset reference is always initialized to nullptr, and to check for null when decrementing the dataset reference.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e"},{"sha":"4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984","author":{"name":"Koan-Sin Tan","email":"0f50d6f3c0f5df9b282683ddabaf63e2d4d09d2c@gmail.com"},"message":"[nnapi delegate] fix a trivial redundant comment and a typo","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984"},{"sha":"a36a8184b802dadf814e3ddb8493f0c4e4192ef8","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #49108 from ROCmSoftwarePlatform:google_upstream_hipsparse_complex

When an attribute value changes in sensitivity, we previously rendered
this in the diff with a `~` update action and a note about the
consequence of the sensitivity change. Since we also suppress the
attribute value, this made it impossible to know if the underlying value
was changing, too, which has significant consequences on the meaning of
the plan.

these are unchanged, we add a note to the sensitivity warning to clarify
that only sensitivity is changing.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tydavis/terraform/commits/5fc3ba37a63d7af032ad0a59ce4b5d016cc44652"},{"sha":"bd4f8d7dea683b0712df320119fba1249bf88ca3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #28738 from hashicorp/alisdair/sensitive-attributes-values-diff

[{"sha":"5fc3ba37a63d7af032ad0a59ce4b5d016cc44652","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Improve sensitivity change warning output

When an attribute value changes in sensitivity, we previously rendered
this in the diff with a `~` update action and a note about the
consequence of the sensitivity change. Since we also suppress the
attribute value, this made it impossible to know if the underlying value
was changing, too, which has significant consequences on the meaning of
the plan.

This commit adds an equality check of the old/new underlying values. If
these are unchanged, we add a note to the sensitivity warning to clarify
that only sensitivity is changing.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5fc3ba37a63d7af032ad0a59ce4b5d016cc44652"}]

[{"sha":"f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e","author":{"name":"Abin Shahab","email":"aa5e48ffaae751ccd8830df151a27b555951f193@linkedin.com"},"message":"Resolves coredump caused by `tf.data.experimental.save` with prefetch

Repeat and prefetch in combination cause the snapshot reader Initialize function to be invoked multiple times.
However, there is nothing to prefetch on the very last iteration. This results in Prefetch issuing a CancelThreads call while the snapshot thread is trying to initialize. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/6446dda92eaadf11d22377e2354307642d739d73/tensorflow/core/kernels/data/prefetch_dataset_op.cc#L151

Currently the dataset reference counting is done asymmetrically. The reference increment happens at the end of initialization, where as the reference decrement
happens in a destructor. When prefetch cancels the snapshot thread, it errors out of the initialization function. And stops calling the reference increment. However, the reference decrement happens regardless, as it is in the destructor which always is invoked during cleanup. This results in an attempt to decrement the null dataset pointer, and therefore a segmentation fault.
This is different from all other dataset ops, where the dataset reference increment happens in the constructor and the decrement happens in the destructor, which are symmetric.

happens in a destructor. When prefetch cancels the snapshot thread, it errors out of the initialization function. And stops calling the reference increment. However, the reference decrement happens regardless, as it is in the destructor which always is invoked during cleanup. This results in an attempt to decrement the null dataset pointer, and therefore a segmentation fault.
This is different from all other dataset ops, where the dataset reference increment happens in the constructor and the decrement happens in the destructor, which are symmetric.

[{"sha":"f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e","author":{"name":"Abin Shahab","email":"aa5e48ffaae751ccd8830df151a27b555951f193@linkedin.com"},"message":"Resolves coredump caused by `tf.data.experimental.save` with prefetch

Repeat and prefetch in combination cause the snapshot reader Initialize function to be invoked multiple times.
However, there is nothing to prefetch on the very last iteration. This results in Prefetch issuing a CancelThreads call while the snapshot thread is trying to initialize. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/6446dda92eaadf11d22377e2354307642d739d73/tensorflow/core/kernels/data/prefetch_dataset_op.cc#L151

Currently the dataset reference counting is done asymmetrically. The reference increment happens at the end of initialization, where as the reference decrement
happens in a destructor. When prefetch cancels the snapshot thread, it errors out of the initialization function. And stops calling the reference increment. However, the reference decrement happens regardless, as it is in the destructor which always is invoked during cleanup. This results in an attempt to decrement the null dataset pointer, and therefore a segmentation fault.
This is different from all other dataset ops, where the dataset reference increment happens in the constructor and the decrement happens in the destructor, which are symmetric.

The solution to this is to ensure that the dataset reference is always initialized to nullptr, and to check for null when decrementing the dataset reference.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e"},{"sha":"4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984","author":{"name":"Koan-Sin Tan","email":"0f50d6f3c0f5df9b282683ddabaf63e2d4d09d2c@gmail.com"},"message":"[nnapi delegate] fix a trivial redundant comment and a typo","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984"},{"sha":"6dfadbcd5fbec0198c4a4ebe3174dd15716ff681","author":{"name":"A. This implementation is based on the example in tf.slim. It exhibits a run time and space complexity of O(T + N), where T is the number of thresholds and N is the size of predictions. Metrics that rely on standard implementation instead exhibit a complexity of O(T * N). It could save a lot of memory when N is large.

Added a unit test to verify the memory consumption. Under eager context, the ratio of memory between old and new approach is between 80 and 500. Set the limit to 50 to avoid the flakiness.

[{"sha":"5c0b694ef3a4b86cdcd7ce03f1b300252ca70a05","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"container: make hostconfig.json non-world-readable (0600)

When writing container's `hostconfig.json`, permissions were set to 0644 (world-
readable). While this is not a security concern (as the `/var/lib/docker/containers`
directory has `0700` or `0701` permissions), there is no real need to have these
permissions, as this file is only accessed by the daemon.

Looking at history for file permissions;

- 06b53e3fc7aca2b3dae32edab08c7662d3e9e7e8 (first implementation) used `0666` (world-writable)
- cf1a6c08fa03aa7020f8f5b414bb9349a9c8371a refactored the code, and removed explicit permissions
- ea3cbd3274664f5b16fce78d7df036f6b5c94e30 introduced atomic writes, and brought back the `0666` permissions
- 3ec8fed7476704f061891d4c421c615da49e30c7 removed world-writable bits, but kept world-readable

This patch updates the permissions to `0600`, matching what's used for `config.v2.json`,
which was updated in ae52cea3ab46e1e728606349fb6baa9a8203f3ed, but forgot to update
`hostconfig.json`.

when the service is fully up and running.
`NotifyAccess=all` is required, since the main process is the wrapper script,

This makes daemon.getExecConfig return a errdefs.Conflict() error if the

a793564b2591035aec5412fbcbcccf220c773a4c

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/aiordache/moby/commits/6eb5720233ddbf00a614e82524ade35a0e3cfc5c"},{"sha":"a432eb4b3a0d06675889153e2993ae8ba8dc9149","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"ContainerExecStart(): don't wrap getExecConfig() errors, and prevent panic

daemon.getExecConfig() already returns typed errors; by wrapping those errors
we may loose the actual reason for failures. Changing the error-type was
originally added in 2d43d93410c29cec87deb9cd940c3b2a8af5fbbb, but I think
it was not intentional to ignore already-typed errors. It was later refactored
in a793564b2591035aec5412fbcbcccf220c773a4c, which added helper functions
to create these errors, but kept the same behavior.

Also adds error-handling to prevent a panic in situations where (although
unlikely) `daemon.containers.Get()` would not return a container.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/aiordache/moby/commits/948e201c1c23c13c8f0c1b94faf4c2bc968826d1"},{"sha":"1ec689c4c2ecda24ed8495451c53072bb0497871","author":{"name":"Michal Rostecki","email":"82ebf970c69340aebb770c3853be5fd96a3eb584@opensuse.org"},"message":"btrfs: Do not disable quota on cleanup

Before this change, cleanup of the btrfs driver (occuring on each daemon
shutdown) resulted in disabling quotas. It was done with an assumption
that quotas can be enabled or disabled on a subvolume level, which is
not true - enabling or disabling quota is always done on a filesystem
level.

That was leading to disabling quota on btrfs filesystems on each daemon
shutdown.

This change fixes that behavior and removes misleading `subvol` prefix
from functions and methods which set up quota (on a filesystem level).

Fixes: #34593
Fixes: 401c8d176743 ("Add disk quota support for btrfs")
Signed-off-by: Michal Rostecki <mrostecki@opensuse.org>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/aiordache/moby/commits/1ec689c4c2ecda24ed8495451c53072bb0497871"},{"sha":"8e362b75cb8cfbc539169cbb5d77c52802f65eb1","author":{"name":"Cam","email":"1041179cbdda366fd7b0347f09255f775170e103@sparr.email"},"message":"docker daemon container stop refactor

this refactors the Stop command to fix a few issues and behaviors that
dont seem completely correct:

1. first it fixes a situation where stop could hang forever (#41579)
2. fixes a behavior where if sending the
stop signal failed, then the code directly sends a -9 signal. If that
fails, it returns without waiting for the process to exit or going
through the full docker kill codepath.
3. fixes a behavior where if sending the stop signal failed, then the
code sends a -9 signal. If that succeeds, then we still go through the
same stop waiting process, and may even go through the docker kill path
again, even though we've already sent a -9.
4. fixes a behavior where the code would wait the full 30 seconds after
sending a stop signal, even if we already know the stop signal failed.

fixes #41579

[{"sha":"f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e","author":{"name":"Abin Shahab","email":"aa5e48ffaae751ccd8830df151a27b555951f193@linkedin.com"},"message":"Resolves coredump caused by `tf.data.experimental.save` with prefetch

Repeat and prefetch in combination cause the snapshot reader Initialize function to be invoked multiple times.
However, there is nothing to prefetch on the very last iteration. This results in Prefetch issuing a CancelThreads call while the snapshot thread is trying to initialize. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/6446dda92eaadf11d22377e2354307642d739d73/tensorflow/core/kernels/data/prefetch_dataset_op.cc#L151

Currently the dataset reference counting is done asymmetrically. The reference increment happens at the end of initialization, where as the reference decrement
happens in a destructor. When prefetch cancels the snapshot thread, it errors out of the initialization function. And stops calling the reference increment. However, the reference decrement happens regardless, as it is in the destructor which always is invoked during cleanup. This results in an attempt to decrement the null dataset pointer, and therefore a segmentation fault.
This is different from all other dataset ops, where the dataset reference increment happens in the constructor and the decrement happens in the destructor, which are symmetric.

The solution to this is to ensure that the dataset reference is always initialized to nullptr, and to check for null when decrementing the dataset reference.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e"},{"sha":"4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984","author":{"name":"Koan-Sin Tan","email":"0f50d6f3c0f5df9b282683ddabaf63e2d4d09d2c@gmail.com"},"message":"[nnapi delegate] fix a trivial redundant comment and a typo","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984"},{"sha":"9ba2e103731f3cebc9c1711d1ef5d51e120c05f4","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #49166 from ashahab:ashahab-save-load-segfault

Works around the corrupted Store state by detecting a broken Fast Refresh remount and forcefully dropping the root and re-mounting the entire tree. This prevents Fibers from getting duplicated in the Store (and in the Components tree). The benefit of this approach is that it doesn't rely on an update or change in behavior to Fast Refresh. (This workaround is pretty dirty, but since it's a DEV-only code path, it's probably okay.)

Note that this change doesn't fix all of the reported issues (see #21442 (comment)) but it does fix some of them.

This commit also slightly refactors the way DevTools assigns and manages unique IDs for Fibers in the backend by removing the indirection of a "primary Fiber" and instead mapping both the primary and alternate.

It also removes the previous cache-on-read behavior of getFiberID and splits the method into three separate functions for different use cases:
* getOrGenerateFiberID – Like the previous function, this method returns an ID or generates and caches a new one if the Fiber hasn't been seen before.
* getFiberIDUnsafe – This function returns an ID if one has already been generated or null if not. (It can be used to e.g. log a message about a Fiber without potentially causing it to leak.)
* getFiberIDThrows – This function returns an ID if one has already been generated or it throws. (It can be used to guarantee expected behavior rather than to silently cause a leak.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/SimenB/react/commits/1e3383a41154cb32d8d6b78b2451ee4dabfcb973"},{"sha":"63927e08438e8a52b41840bd583a07b3ceb2956e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Fixed another Symbol concatenation issue with DevTools format() util (#21521)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/SimenB/react/commits/63927e08438e8a52b41840bd583a07b3ceb2956e"},{"sha":"4d402cdda007f4c0f32336111f9debc8edc18eb2","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Preparing DevTools 4.13.2 -> 4.13.3 for release","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/SimenB/react/commits/4d402cdda007f4c0f32336111f9debc8edc18eb2"},{"sha":"343776fc9071f9e8c8a1dee0166c033bf381f04d","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Added React entry-points change to DevTools changelog","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/SimenB/react/commits/343776fc9071f9e8c8a1dee0166c033bf381f04d"}]

Green","email":"97e77871b5fcc4941bebceb4338c97c1fd149f8c@google.com"},"message":"micro: Printed memory plan layout changes

Reformats output of GreedyMemoryPlanner:PrintMemoryPlan() to make it
simpler to interpret.

Per-buffer info line improvements:

(a) Reduces text quantity to make it easier to scan for information.
(b) Moves size to near front line, to make it simpler for the eye to
    find this information.
(c) Includes ordinal letter used in per-time display below to make it
    simpler to cross-reference.

Per time improvements:

(a) Includes tick number. This is useful in larger models for cross

Repeat and prefetch in combination cause the snapshot reader Initialize function to be invoked multiple times.
However, there is nothing to prefetch on the very last iteration. This results in Prefetch issuing a CancelThreads call while the snapshot thread is trying to initialize. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/6446dda92eaadf11d22377e2354307642d739d73/tensorflow/core/kernels/data/prefetch_dataset_op.cc#L151

Currently the dataset reference counting is done asymmetrically. The reference increment happens at the end of initialization, where as the reference decrement
happens in a destructor. When prefetch cancels the snapshot thread, it errors out of the initialization function. And stops calling the reference increment. However, the reference decrement happens regardless, as it is in the destructor which always is invoked during cleanup. This results in an attempt to decrement the null dataset pointer, and therefore a segmentation fault.
This is different from all other dataset ops, where the dataset reference increment happens in the constructor and the decrement happens in the destructor, which are symmetric.

The solution to this is to ensure that the dataset reference is always initialized to nullptr, and to check for null when decrementing the dataset reference.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e"},{"sha":"f060174926471e8e882ff2cecb5660010c56a721","author":{"name":"Ashutosh Hathidara","email":"8221b1507f31f1542863efde7afcbe0f973dd311@legatohealth.com"},"message":"Merge remote-tracking branch 'upstream/master' into reduce_variance","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/f060174926471e8e882ff2cecb5660010c56a721"},{"sha":"4450889cd79f5ae92f363fd9be5fb03721aa22ab","author":{"name":"Ashutosh Hathidara","email":"8221b1507f31f1542863efde7afcbe0f973dd311@legatohealth.com"},"message":"Implemented reduce_variance for ragged","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/4450889cd79f5ae92f363fd9be5fb03721aa22ab"}]

[{"sha":"82b7b25b1b6efe7c362a1d59d8a0ed8d5e1e7a51","author":{"name":"Eugene Zhulenev","email":"117600c937fb2af1218bd1d47c746d36a58fc7b4@google.com"},"message":"[tf:jit] Resolve statically known constraints during clustering

Stop constraints propagation early if they can be resolved statically from tensor type. This is mostly a performance improvement change to stop large IR traversals early, if we know for sure that all constraints will be satisfied.

As a side effect only unresolved constraints will be added to the compiled function signature, which makes it easier to read.

[{"sha":"1e3383a41154cb32d8d6b78b2451ee4dabfcb973","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"DevTools: Reload all roots after Fast Refresh force remount (#21516)

Works around the corrupted Store state by detecting a broken Fast Refresh remount and forcefully dropping the root and re-mounting the entire tree. This prevents Fibers from getting duplicated in the Store (and in the Components tree). The benefit of this approach is that it doesn't rely on an update or change in behavior to Fast Refresh. (This workaround is pretty dirty, but since it's a DEV-only code path, it's probably okay.)

Note that this change doesn't fix all of the reported issues (see #21442 (comment)) but it does fix some of them.

This commit also slightly refactors the way DevTools assigns and manages unique IDs for Fibers in the backend by removing the indirection of a "primary Fiber" and instead mapping both the primary and alternate.

It also removes the previous cache-on-read behavior of getFiberID and splits the method into three separate functions for different use cases:
* getOrGenerateFiberID – Like the previous function, this method returns an ID or generates and caches a new one if the Fiber hasn't been seen before.
* getFiberIDUnsafe – This function returns an ID if one has already been generated or null if not. (It can be used to e.g. log a message about a Fiber without potentially causing it to leak.)
* getFiberIDThrows – This function returns an ID if one has already been generated or it throws. Works around the corrupted Store state by detecting a broken Fast Refresh remount and forcefully dropping the root and re-mounting the entire tree. This prevents Fibers from getting duplicated in the Store (and in the Components tree). The benefit of this approach is that it doesn't rely on an update or change in behavior to Fast Refresh. (This workaround is pretty dirty, but since it's a DEV-only code path, it's probably okay.)

Note that this change doesn't fix all of the reported issues (see #21442 (comment)) but it does fix some of them.

This commit also slightly refactors the way DevTools assigns and manages unique IDs for Fibers in the backend by removing the indirection of a "primary Fiber" and instead mapping both the primary and alternate.

It also removes the previous cache-on-read behavior of getFiberID and splits the method into three separate functions for different use cases:
* getOrGenerateFiberID – Like the previous function, this method returns an ID or generates and caches a new one if the Fiber hasn't been seen before.
* getFiberIDUnsafe – This function returns an ID if one has already been generated or null if not. (It can be used to e.g. log a message about a Fiber without potentially causing it to leak.)
* getFiberIDThrows – This function returns an ID if one has already been generated or it throws. [{"sha":"52809d94c7c2074f8bbdc7bc0df9975452e63807","author":{"name":"Antonio Sanchez","email":"d7c4f796bb044488ce75bcb289e0b6840bbb0be8@google.com"},"message":"Replace sleep() with Env::Default()->SleepForMicroseconds().

The existing `sleep` call is not platform independent, and for some reason
relies on a custom definition inside a modified Eigen header.  Removing
the definition from the Eigen header and replacing the call with
`Env::Default()->SleepForMicroseconds` is more consistent with
existing code.

The next Eigen update removes the dependence on the `Windows.h` header,
breaking the original `sleep()` calls.

Reformats output of GreedyMemoryPlanner:PrintMemoryPlan() to make it
simpler to interpret.

Per-buffer info line improvements:

(a) Reduces text quantity to make it easier to scan for information.
(b) Moves size to near front line, to make it simpler for the eye to
    find this information.
(c) Includes ordinal letter used in per-time display below to make it
    simpler to cross-reference.

Per time improvements:

(a) Includes tick number. This is useful in larger models for cross
    referencing to the per-buffer information and also for helping to
    determine the actual operation being executed at that time.

[{"sha":"5fc3ba37a63d7af032ad0a59ce4b5d016cc44652","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Improve sensitivity change warning output

When an attribute value changes in sensitivity, we previously rendered
this in the diff with a `~` update action and a note about the
consequence of the sensitivity change. Since we also suppress the
attribute value, this made it impossible to know if the underlying value
was changing, too, which has significant consequences on the meaning of
the plan.

This commit adds an equality check of the old/new underlying values. If
these are unchanged, we add a note to the sensitivity warning to clarify
that only sensitivity is changing.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5fc3ba37a63d7af032ad0a59ce4b5d016cc44652"},{"sha":"bd4f8d7dea683b0712df320119fba1249bf88ca3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #28738 from hashicorp/alisdair/sensitive-attributes-values-diff

Works around the corrupted Store state by detecting a broken Fast Refresh remount and forcefully dropping the root and re-mounting the entire tree. This prevents Fibers from getting duplicated in the Store (and in the Components tree). The benefit of this approach is that it doesn't rely on an update or change in behavior to Fast Refresh. (This workaround is pretty dirty, but since it's a DEV-only code path, it's probably okay.)

Note that this change doesn't fix all of the reported issues (see #21442 (comment)) but it does fix some of them.

This commit also slightly refactors the way DevTools assigns and manages unique IDs for Fibers in the backend by removing the indirection of a "primary Fiber" and instead mapping both the primary and alternate.

It also removes the previous cache-on-read behavior of getFiberID and splits the method into three separate functions for different use cases:
* getOrGenerateFiberID – Like the previous function, this method returns an ID or generates and caches a new one if the Fiber hasn't been seen before.
* getFiberIDUnsafe – This function returns an ID if one has already been generated or null if not. (It can be used to e.g. log a message about a Fiber without potentially causing it to leak.)
* getFiberIDThrows – This function returns an ID if one has already been generated or it throws. (It can be used to guarantee expected behavior rather than to silently cause a leak.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chojar/react/commits/1e3383a41154cb32d8d6b78b2451ee4dabfcb973"},{"sha":"63927e08438e8a52b41840bd583a07b3ceb2956e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Fixed another Symbol concatenation issue with DevTools format() util (#21521)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chojar/react/commits/63927e08438e8a52b41840bd583a07b3ceb2956e"},{"sha":"4d402cdda007f4c0f32336111f9debc8edc18eb2","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Preparing DevTools 4.13.2 -> 4.13.3 for release","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chojar/react/commits/4d402cdda007f4c0f32336111f9debc8edc18eb2"},{"sha":"343776fc9071f9e8c8a1dee0166c033bf381f04d","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Added React entry-points change to DevTools changelog","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chojar/react/commits/343776fc9071f9e8c8a1dee0166c033bf381f04d"}]

Reformats output of GreedyMemoryPlanner:PrintMemoryPlan() to make it
simpler to interpret.

Per-buffer info line improvements:

(a) Reduces text quantity to make it easier to scan for information.
(b) Moves size to near front line, to make it simpler for the eye to
    find this information.
(c) Includes ordinal letter used in per-time display below to make it
    simpler to cross-reference.

Per time improvements:

(a) Includes tick number. This is useful in larger models for cross
    referencing to the per-buffer information and also for helping to
    determine the actual operation being executed at that time.
(b) Includes total memory use of buffers, which helps to more clearly
    identify memory bottlenecks.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/0f32b446cf8cc140f8eaf02c1671e842ad126338"},{"sha":"1af9d9130ca3186125c72c6f72a4fbb60763e056","author":{"name":"Alan Green","email":"97e77871b5fcc4941bebceb4338c97c1fd149f8c@google.com"},"message":"micro: fix unused-variable-warning

[{"sha":"d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605","author":{"name":"Rémi Lapeyre","email":"953e8a3102147c156e7cfddb2d9937b841ad931f@lenstra.fr"},"message":"Use a global sequence to create the IDs for each workspace

Until now the default workspace for every project would have the ID 1,
which would make it impossible to lock them at the same time since we
use the ID to identify the lock. With a global sequence to generate the
IDs, the default workspace will now have a different ID for each project
and it will be possible to lock multiple unrelated projects at the same
time.

If an old version of Terraform tries to get the lock on a project created
with this new version it will work as we continue to use the ID of the
workspace, we just change the way we generate them.

If this version tries to get a lock on a project created by an old
version of Terraform it will work as usual, but we may encounter a
conflict with another unrelated project. This is already the current
behavior so it's not an issue to persist this behavior. As users migrate
to an up-to-date version of Terraform this will stop.

Projects already present in the database will keep their conflicting IDs,
I did not wanted to change them as users may be reading the states
directly in the database for some reason. They can if they want change
them manually to remove conflicts, newly created projects will work
without manual intervention.

Closes https://github.com/hashicorp/terraform/issues/22833","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605"},{"sha":"45b795b3fd02d5177666218c3703e26252eeb745","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"Update CHANGELOG.md","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/45b795b3fd02d5177666218c3703e26252eeb745"},{"sha":"47a682141a3d794f98035f4ef9fb0fe2014b764e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remote provisioners require a connection config","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/47a682141a3d794f98035f4ef9fb0fe2014b764e"},{"sha":"2b252ac677f1d99adcf08202c3047be2478a1055","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27910 from hashicorp/jbardin/remote-provisioners

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views: Fix missing source in diagnostic output

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

The existing `sleep` call is not platform independent, and for some reason
relies on a custom definition inside a modified Eigen header.  Removing
the definition from the Eigen header and replacing the call with
`Env::Default()->SleepForMicroseconds` is more consistent with
existing code.

The next Eigen update removes the dependence on the `Windows.h` header,
breaking the original `sleep()` calls.

[{"sha":"1e3383a41154cb32d8d6b78b2451ee4dabfcb973","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"DevTools: Reload all roots after Fast Refresh force remount (#21516)

Works around the corrupted Store state by detecting a broken Fast Refresh remount and forcefully dropping the root and re-mounting the entire tree. This prevents Fibers from getting duplicated in the Store (and in the Components tree). The benefit of this approach is that it doesn't rely on an update or change in behavior to Fast Refresh. (This workaround is pretty dirty, but since it's a DEV-only code path, it's probably okay.)

Note that this change doesn't fix all of the reported issues (see #21442 (comment)) but it does fix some of them.

This commit also slightly refactors the way DevTools assigns and manages unique IDs for Fibers in the backend by removing the indirection of a "primary Fiber" and instead mapping both the primary and alternate.

It also removes the previous cache-on-read behavior of getFiberID and splits the method into three separate functions for different use cases:
* getOrGenerateFiberID – Like the previous function, this method returns an ID or generates and caches a new one if the Fiber hasn't been seen before.
* getFiberIDUnsafe – This function returns an ID if one has already been generated or null if not. (It can be used to e.g. log a message about a Fiber without potentially causing it to leak.)
* getFiberIDThrows – This function returns an ID if one has already been generated or it throws. Repeat and prefetch in combination cause the snapshot reader Initialize function to be invoked multiple times.
However, there is nothing to prefetch on the very last iteration. This results in Prefetch issuing a CancelThreads call while the snapshot thread is trying to initialize. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/6446dda92eaadf11d22377e2354307642d739d73/tensorflow/core/kernels/data/prefetch_dataset_op.cc#L151

Currently the dataset reference counting is done asymmetrically. The reference increment happens at the end of initialization, where as the reference decrement
happens in a destructor. When prefetch cancels the snapshot thread, it errors out of the initialization function. And stops calling the reference increment. However, the reference decrement happens regardless, as it is in the destructor which always is invoked during cleanup. This results in an attempt to decrement the null dataset pointer, and therefore a segmentation fault.
This is different from all other dataset ops, where the dataset reference increment happens in the constructor and the decrement happens in the destructor, which are symmetric.

The solution to this is to ensure that the dataset reference is always initialized to nullptr, and to check for null when decrementing the dataset reference.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e"},{"sha":"bdc55b1f6d05be3ca9f0b344da1c14943aaee988","author":{"name":"Ashutosh Hathidara","email":"8221b1507f31f1542863efde7afcbe0f973dd311@legatohealth.com"},"message":"Fixed Accuracy to be able to transform dynamically","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/bdc55b1f6d05be3ca9f0b344da1c14943aaee988"},{"sha":"ad1bdcfc4dda846a588b44755f82f56a012f5cc8","author":{"name":"Lu Wang","email":"bb4ea195588a4447f4ab0d60d396369d687bcd9e@google.com"},"message":"Fix Java API doc errors in TFLite Java Library and Support Library

[{"sha":"81814091dec0e7f151da1b0560675312851ea3f9","author":{"name":"stevenireeves","email":"e97782b0e41fb044f04f25b964a5a11795fed361@gmail.com"},"message":"Adding Complex Types to existing HipSparse Functions.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yongtang/tensorflow/commits/81814091dec0e7f151da1b0560675312851ea3f9"},{"sha":"d7fcf7374d1268ab544d526c6792e61100e47436","author":{"name":"stevenireeves","email":"e97782b0e41fb044f04f25b964a5a11795fed361@gmail.com"},"message":"Adding the changes from commit https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/061dec2ab7fd91f369598b2223ba388e5b10777d, so this PR passes the pylint test in Ubuntu Sanity","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yongtang/tensorflow/commits/d7fcf7374d1268ab544d526c6792e61100e47436"},{"sha":"754269c236e06a8347ce599545ab418ab40653a2","author":{"name":"Steven I Reeves","email":"e97782b0e41fb044f04f25b964a5a11795fed361@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge branch 'master' into google_upstream_hipsparse_complex","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yongtang/tensorflow/commits/754269c236e06a8347ce599545ab418ab40653a2"},{"sha":"f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e","author":{"name":"Abin Shahab","email":"aa5e48ffaae751ccd8830df151a27b555951f193@linkedin.com"},"message":"Resolves coredump caused by `tf.data.experimental.save` with prefetch

Repeat and prefetch in combination cause the snapshot reader Initialize function to be invoked multiple times.
However, there is nothing to prefetch on the very last iteration. This results in Prefetch issuing a CancelThreads call while the snapshot thread is trying to initialize. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/6446dda92eaadf11d22377e2354307642d739d73/tensorflow/core/kernels/data/prefetch_dataset_op.cc#L151

Currently the dataset reference counting is done asymmetrically. The reference increment happens at the end of initialization, where as the reference decrement
happens in a destructor. When prefetch cancels the snapshot thread, it errors out of the initialization function. And stops calling the reference increment. However, the reference decrement happens regardless, as it is in the destructor which always is invoked during cleanup. This results in an attempt to decrement the null dataset pointer, and therefore a segmentation fault.
This is different from all other dataset ops, where the dataset reference increment happens in the constructor and the decrement happens in the destructor, which are symmetric.

The solution to this is to ensure that the dataset reference is always initialized to nullptr, and to check for null when decrementing the dataset reference.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yongtang/tensorflow/commits/f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e"},{"sha":"bdc55b1f6d05be3ca9f0b344da1c14943aaee988","author":{"name":"Ashutosh Hathidara","email":"8221b1507f31f1542863efde7afcbe0f973dd311@legatohealth.com"},"message":"Fixed Accuracy to be able to transform dynamically","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yongtang/tensorflow/commits/bdc55b1f6d05be3ca9f0b344da1c14943aaee988"},{"sha":"4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984","author":{"name":"Koan-Sin Tan","email":"0f50d6f3c0f5df9b282683ddabaf63e2d4d09d2c@gmail.com"},"message":"[nnapi delegate] fix a trivial redundant comment and a typo","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yongtang/tensorflow/commits/4dd58e628b4db36ab4cbb6cb8f17df11c3e0e984"},{"sha":"a8d2f82e2be0676004a94af438c41a0c9036b4e1","author":{"name":"Lu Wang","email":"bb4ea195588a4447f4ab0d60d396369d687bcd9e@google.com"},"message":"Remove messages on potential Task C++ API change

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Allow localized disabling of tests for asan/msan/tsan/ubsan.

Currently we can disable entire test targets via the bazel tags `noasan`,
`nomsan`, `notsan`, `noubsan`.  However, in some instances, we may expect
one particular edge-case to fail a sanitizer test (for known reason), but
still want the rest of the test suite to be analyzed. By disabling individual
test methods or parts thereof locally, we allow for this without the need to
separate the offending case into a different target.

There already was some functionality in tflite, which seems to currently
be unused (though has been previously to locally skip tests).
Refactored and moved to tf so can be more widely used.

Also added corresponding defines to the `.bazelrc` file.

[{"sha":"1e3383a41154cb32d8d6b78b2451ee4dabfcb973","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"DevTools: Reload all roots after Fast Refresh force remount (#21516)

Works around the corrupted Store state by detecting a broken Fast Refresh remount and forcefully dropping the root and re-mounting the entire tree. This prevents Fibers from getting duplicated in the Store (and in the Components tree). The benefit of this approach is that it doesn't rely on an update or change in behavior to Fast Refresh. (This workaround is pretty dirty, but since it's a DEV-only code path, it's probably okay.)

Note that this change doesn't fix all of the reported issues (see #21442 (comment)) but it does fix some of them.

This commit also slightly refactors the way DevTools assigns and manages unique IDs for Fibers in the backend by removing the indirection of a "primary Fiber" and instead mapping both the primary and alternate.

It also removes the previous cache-on-read behavior of getFiberID and splits the method into three separate functions for different use cases:
* getOrGenerateFiberID – Like the previous function, this method returns an ID or generates and caches a new one if the Fiber hasn't been seen before.
* getFiberIDUnsafe – This function returns an ID if one has already been generated or null if not. (It can be used to e.g. log a message about a Fiber without potentially causing it to leak.)
* getFiberIDThrows – This function returns an ID if one has already been generated or it throws. (It can be used to guarantee expected behavior rather than to silently cause a leak.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/facebook/react/commits/1e3383a41154cb32d8d6b78b2451ee4dabfcb973"}]

Reformats output of GreedyMemoryPlanner:PrintMemoryPlan() to make it
simpler to interpret.

Per-buffer info line improvements:

(a) Reduces text quantity to make it easier to scan for information.
(b) Moves size to near front line, to make it simpler for the eye to
    find this information.
(c) Includes ordinal letter used in per-time display below to make it

[{"sha":"8c00296c7444045bf948fe79d456cc11959e85e3","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Account for another DevTools + Fast Refresh edge case

DevTools now 'untrack' Fibers (cleans up the ID-to-Fiber mapping) after a slight delay in order to support a Fast Refresh edge case:
1. Component type is updated and Fast Refresh schedules an update+remount.
2. flushPendingErrorsAndWarningsAfterDelay() runs, sees the old Fiber is no longer mounted (it's been disconnected by Fast Refresh), and calls untrackFiberID() to clear it from the Map.
3. React flushes pending passive effects before it runs the next render, which logs an error or warning, which causes a new ID to be generated for this Fiber.
4. DevTools now tries to unmount the old Component with the new ID.

The underlying problem here is the premature clearing of the Fiber ID, but DevTools has no way to detect that a given Fiber has been scheduled for Fast Refresh. (The '_debugNeedsRemount' flag won't necessarily be set.)

The best we can do is to delay untracking by a small amount, and give React time to process the Fast Refresh delay.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bvaughn/react/commits/8c00296c7444045bf948fe79d456cc11959e85e3"}]

Works around the corrupted Store state by detecting a broken Fast Refresh remount and forcefully dropping the root and re-mounting the entire tree. This prevents Fibers from getting duplicated in the Store (and in the Components tree). The benefit of this approach is that it doesn't rely on an update or change in behavior to Fast Refresh. (This workaround is pretty dirty, but since it's a DEV-only code path, it's probably okay.)

Note that this change doesn't fix all of the reported issues (see #21442 (comment)) but it does fix some of them.

This commit also slightly refactors the way DevTools assigns and manages unique IDs for Fibers in the backend by removing the indirection of a "primary Fiber" and instead mapping both the primary and alternate.

It also removes the previous cache-on-read behavior of getFiberID and splits the method into three separate functions for different use cases:
* getOrGenerateFiberID – Like the previous function, this method returns an ID or generates and caches a new one if the Fiber hasn't been seen before.
* getFiberIDUnsafe – This function returns an ID if one has already been generated or null if not. (It can be used to e.g. log a message about a Fiber without potentially causing it to leak.)
* getFiberIDThrows – This function returns an ID if one has already been generated or it throws. Works around the corrupted Store state by detecting a broken Fast Refresh remount and forcefully dropping the root and re-mounting the entire tree. This prevents Fibers from getting duplicated in the Store (and in the Components tree). The benefit of this approach is that it doesn't rely on an update or change in behavior to Fast Refresh. (This workaround is pretty dirty, but since it's a DEV-only code path, it's probably okay.)

Note that this change doesn't fix all of the reported issues (see #21442 (comment)) but it does fix some of them.

This commit also slightly refactors the way DevTools assigns and manages unique IDs for Fibers in the backend by removing the indirection of a "primary Fiber" and instead mapping both the primary and alternate.

It also removes the previous cache-on-read behavior of getFiberID and splits the method into three separate functions for different use cases:
* getOrGenerateFiberID – Like the previous function, this method returns an ID or generates and caches a new one if the Fiber hasn't been seen before.

simpler to interpret.

Per-buffer info line improvements:

(a) Reduces text quantity to make it easier to scan for information.
(b) Moves size to near front line, to make it simpler for the eye to
    find this information.
(c) Includes ordinal letter used in per-time display below to make it
    simpler to cross-reference.

Per time improvements:

(a) Includes tick number. This is useful in larger models for cross
    referencing to the per-buffer information and also for helping to
    determine the actual operation being executed at that time.

Works around the corrupted Store state by detecting a broken Fast Refresh remount and forcefully dropping the root and re-mounting the entire tree. This prevents Fibers from getting duplicated in the Store (and in the Components tree). The benefit of this approach is that it doesn't rely on an update or change in behavior to Fast Refresh. (This workaround is pretty dirty, but since it's a DEV-only code path, it's probably okay.)

Note that this change doesn't fix all of the reported issues (see #21442 (comment)) but it does fix some of them.

This commit also slightly refactors the way DevTools assigns and manages unique IDs for Fibers in the backend by removing the indirection of a "primary Fiber" and instead mapping both the primary and alternate.

It also removes the previous cache-on-read behavior of getFiberID and splits the method into three separate functions for different use cases:
* getOrGenerateFiberID – Like the previous function, this method returns an ID or generates and caches a new one if the Fiber hasn't been seen before.
* getFiberIDUnsafe – This function returns an ID if one has already been generated or null if not. (It can be used to e.g. log a message about a Fiber without potentially causing it to leak.)
* getFiberIDThrows – This function returns an ID if one has already been generated or it throws. (It can be used to guarantee expected behavior rather than to silently cause a leak.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MLH-Fellowship/react/commits/1e3383a41154cb32d8d6b78b2451ee4dabfcb973"},{"sha":"63927e08438e8a52b41840bd583a07b3ceb2956e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Fixed another Symbol concatenation issue with DevTools format() util (#21521)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MLH-Fellowship/react/commits/63927e08438e8a52b41840bd583a07b3ceb2956e"}]

Works around the corrupted Store state by detecting a broken Fast Refresh remount and forcefully dropping the root and re-mounting the entire tree. This prevents Fibers from getting duplicated in the Store (and in the Components tree). The benefit of this approach is that it doesn't rely on an update or change in behavior to Fast Refresh. (This workaround is pretty dirty, but since it's a DEV-only code path, it's probably okay.)

Note that this change doesn't fix all of the reported issues (see #21442 (comment)) but it does fix some of them.

This commit also slightly refactors the way DevTools assigns and manages unique IDs for Fibers in the backend by removing the indirection of a "primary Fiber" and instead mapping both the primary and alternate.

It also removes the previous cache-on-read behavior of getFiberID and splits the method into three separate functions for different use cases:
* getOrGenerateFiberID – Like the previous function, this method returns an ID or generates and caches a new one if the Fiber hasn't been seen before.
* getFiberIDUnsafe – This function returns an ID if one has already been generated or null if not. (It can be used to e.g. log a message about a Fiber without potentially causing it to leak.)
* getFiberIDThrows – This function returns an ID if one has already been generated or it throws. (It can be used to guarantee expected behavior rather than to silently cause a leak.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JCofman/react/commits/1e3383a41154cb32d8d6b78b2451ee4dabfcb973"},{"sha":"63927e08438e8a52b41840bd583a07b3ceb2956e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Fixed another Symbol concatenation issue with DevTools format() util (#21521)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JCofman/react/commits/63927e08438e8a52b41840bd583a07b3ceb2956e"}]

    find this information.

    simpler to cross-reference.

(a) Includes tick number. This is useful in larger models for cross

    determine the actual operation being executed at that time.

Repeat and prefetch in combination cause the snapshot reader Initialize function to be invoked multiple times.
However, there is nothing to prefetch on the very last iteration. This results in Prefetch issuing a CancelThreads call while the snapshot thread is trying to initialize. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/6446dda92eaadf11d22377e2354307642d739d73/tensorflow/core/kernels/data/prefetch_dataset_op.cc#L151

Currently the dataset reference counting is done asymmetrically. The reference increment happens at the end of initialization, where as the reference decrement
happens in a destructor. When prefetch cancels the snapshot thread, it errors out of the initialization function. And stops calling the reference increment. However, the reference decrement happens regardless, as it is in the destructor which always is invoked during cleanup. This results in an attempt to decrement the null dataset pointer, and therefore a segmentation fault.
This is different from all other dataset ops, where the dataset reference increment happens in the constructor and the decrement happens in the destructor, which are symmetric.

The solution to this is to ensure that the dataset reference is always initialized to nullptr, and to check for null when decrementing the dataset reference.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clayne/tensorflow/commits/f862ede4402cedad052bb72e6a7a025f00a5188e"},{"sha":"f060174926471e8e882ff2cecb5660010c56a721","author":{"name":"Ashutosh Hathidara","email":"8221b1507f31f1542863efde7afcbe0f973dd311@legatohealth.com"},"message":"Merge remote-tracking branch 'upstream/master' into reduce_variance","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clayne/tensorflow/commits/f060174926471e8e882ff2cecb5660010c56a721"},{"sha":"4450889cd79f5ae92f363fd9be5fb03721aa22ab","author":{"name":"Ashutosh Hathidara","email":"8221b1507f31f1542863efde7afcbe0f973dd311@legatohealth.com"},"message":"Implemented reduce_variance for ragged","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clayne/tensorflow/commits/4450889cd79f5ae92f363fd9be5fb03721aa22ab"}]
